pageContext.claim: “During that year, our economy grew at 3 percent. And if the Fed didn't raise interest rates, frankly, it would've been much higher than 3 percent. And the stock market, as high as it's been, would've been at least, I think, probably anywhere from seven to ten thousand points higher.”
pageContext.analysis: There is no evidence this is the case. The Federal Reserve modestly raised interest rates because the Fed’s congressionally set dual mandate is maximum employment and stable prices. It is not maximum stock market values.
